# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: profinet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:profinet/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:profinet/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:profinet/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:profinet/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:profinet/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:profinet/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:profinet/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:profinet/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet can also refer to the use of standard Ethernet protocols with rugged connectors and extended temperature switches in an industrial environment, for automation or process control.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Components used in plant process areas must be designed to work in harsh environments of temperature extremes, humidity, and vibration that exceed the ranges for information technology equipment intended for installation in controlled environments.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] The use of fiber-optic Ethernet variants reduces the problems of electrical noise and provides electrical isolation.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Some industrial networks emphasized deterministic delivery of transmitted data, whereas Ethernet used collision detection which made transport time for individual data packets difficult to estimate with increasing network traffic.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Typically, industrial uses of Ethernet employ full-duplex standards and other methods so that collisions do not unacceptably influence transmission times.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Industrial use requires consideration of the environment in which the equipment must operate.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Factory equipment must tolerate a wider range of temperature, vibration, physical contamination and electrical noise than equipment installed in dedicated information-technology wiring closets.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Since critical process control may rely on an Ethernet link, the economic cost of interruptions may be high and high availability is therefore an essential criterion.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet networks must interoperate with both current and legacy systems, and must provide predictable performance and maintainability.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] In addition to physical compatibility and low-level transport protocols, a practical industrial Ethernet system must also provide interoperability of higher levels of the OSI model.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] An industrial network must provide security both from intrusions from outside the plant, and inadvertent or unauthorized use within the plant.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] When an industrial network must connect to an office network or external networks, a firewall system can be inserted to control exchange of data between the networks.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] This network separation preserves the performance and reliability of the industrial network.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) communicate using one of several possible open or proprietary protocols, such as EtherNet/IP, EtherCAT, Modbus, Sinec H1, Profibus, CANopen, DeviceNet or FOUNDATION Fieldbus.
[src:profinet/industrial-ethernet] The idea to use standard Ethernet makes these systems more interoperable.
[src:profinet/profinet] Profinet implements the interfacing to peripherals.
[src:profinet/profinet] It defines the communication with field connected peripheral devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] Its basis is a cascading real-time concept.
[src:profinet/profinet] Profinet defines the entire data exchange between controllers (called "IO-Controllers") and the devices (called "IO-Devices"), as well as parameter setting and diagnosis.
[src:profinet/profinet] IO-Controllers are typically a PLC, DCS, or IPC; whereas IO-Devices can be varied: I/O blocks, drives, sensors, or actuators.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Profinet protocol is designed for the fast data exchange between Ethernet-based field devices and follows the provider-consumer model.
[src:profinet/profinet] Field devices in a subordinate Profibus line can be integrated in the Profinet system seamlessly via an IO-Proxy (representative of a subordinate bus system).
[src:profinet/profinet] A minimal Profinet **IO-System** consists of at least one IO-Controller that controls one or more IO-Devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition, one or more IO-Supervisors can optionally be switched on temporarily for the engineering of the IO-Devices if required.
[src:profinet/profinet] If two IO-Systems are in the same IP network, the IO-Controllers can also share an input signal as shared input, in which they have read access to the same submodule in an IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] This simplifies the combination of a PLC with a separate safety controller or motion control.
[src:profinet/profinet] Likewise, an entire IO-Device can be shared as a shared device, in which individual submodules of an IO-Device are assigned to different IO-Controllers.
[src:profinet/profinet] Each automation device with an Ethernet interface can simultaneously fulfill the functionality of an IO-Controller and an IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] If a controller for a partner controller acts as an IO-Device and simultaneously controls its periphery as an IO-Controller, the tasks between controllers can be coordinated without additional devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] An **Application Relation** (AR) is established between an IO-Controller and an IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] These ARs are used to define **Communication Relations** (CR) with different characteristics for the transfer of parameters, cyclic exchange of data and handling of alarms.
[src:profinet/profinet] Profinet is also increasingly being used in critical applications.
[src:profinet/profinet] There is always a risk that the required functions cannot be fulfilled.
[src:profinet/profinet] This risk can be reduced by specific measures as identified by a dependability analyses.
[src:profinet/profinet] **Availability:** Increasing the availability.
[src:profinet/profinet] In the event of a fault, the system should still be able to perform the minimum required function.
[src:profinet/profinet] **Security:** Information security is to ensure the integrity of the system.
[src:profinet/profinet] These goals can interfere with or complement each other.
[src:profinet/profinet] Profisafe implements safe communication via a profile, i.e. via a special format of the user data and a special protocol.
[src:profinet/profinet] It is designed as a separate layer on top of the fieldbus application layer to reduce the probability of data transmission errors.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Profisafe messages use standard fieldbus cables and messages.
[src:profinet/profinet] They do not depend on error detection mechanisms of underlying transmission channels, and thus supports securing of whole communication paths, including backplanes inside controllers or remote I/O.
[src:profinet/profinet] and is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:profinet/profinet] High availability is one of the most important requirements in industrial automation, both in factory and process automation.
[src:profinet/profinet] The availability of an automation system can be increased by adding redundancy for critical elements.
[src:profinet/profinet] A distinction can be made between system and media redundancy.
[src:profinet/profinet] System redundancy can also be implemented with Profinet to increase availability.
[src:profinet/profinet] In this case, two IO-Controllers that control the same IO-Device are configured.
[src:profinet/profinet] The active IO-Controller marks its output data as primary.
[src:profinet/profinet] Output data that is not marked is ignored by an IO-Device in a redundant IO-System.
[src:profinet/profinet] In the event of an error, the second IO-Controller can therefore take control of all IO-Devices without interruption by marking its output data as primary.
[src:profinet/profinet] How the two IO-Controllers synchronize their tasks is not defined in Profinet and is implemented differently by the various manufacturers offering redundant control systems.
[src:profinet/profinet] Profinet offers two media redundancy solutions.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Media Redundancy Protocol (MRP) allows the creation of a protocol-independent ring topology with a switching time of less than 50 ms.
[src:profinet/profinet] This is often sufficient for standard real-time communication with Profinet.
[src:profinet/profinet] To switch over the redundancy in the event of an error without time delay, the "Media Redundancy for Planned Duplication" (MRPD) must be used as a seamless media redundancy concept.
[src:profinet/profinet] In the MRPD, the cyclic real-time data is transmitted in both directions in the ring-shaped topology.
[src:profinet/profinet] A time stamp in the data packet allows the receiver to remove the redundant duplicates.
[src:profinet/profinet] The IT security concept for Profinet assumes a defense-in-depth approach.
[src:profinet/profinet] In this approach, the production plant is protected against attacks, particularly from outside, by a multi-level perimeter, including firewalls.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition, further protection is possible within the plant by dividing it into zones using firewalls.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition, a security component test ensures that the Profinet components are resistant to overload to a defined extent.
[src:profinet/profinet] This concept is supported by organizational measures in the production plant within the framework of a security management system according to ISO 27001.
[src:profinet/profinet] For a smooth interaction of the devices involved in an automation solution, they must correspond in their basic functions and services.
[src:profinet/profinet] Standardization is achieved by "profiles" with binding specifications for functions and services.
[src:profinet/profinet] The possible functions of communication with Profinet are restricted and additional specifications regarding the function of the field device are prescribed.
[src:profinet/profinet] These can be cross-device class properties such as a safety-relevant behavior (Common Application Profiles) or device class specific properties (Specific Application Profiles).
[src:profinet/profinet] PROFIdrive is the modular device profile for drive devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] It was jointly developed by manufacturers and users in the 1990s and since then, in conjunction with Profibus and, from version 4.0, also with Profinet, it has covered the entire range from the simplest to the most demanding drive solutions.
[src:profinet/profinet] Another profile is PROFIenergy which includes services for real time monitoring of energy demand.
[src:profinet/profinet] This was requested in 2009 by the AIDA group of German automotive Manufacturers (Audi, BMW, Mercedes-Benz, Porsche and Volkswagen ) who wished to have a standardised way of actively managing energy usage in their plants.
[src:profinet/profinet] Modern process devices have their own intelligence and can take over part of the information processing or the overall functionality in automation systems.
[src:profinet/profinet] For integration into a Profinet system, a two-wire Ethernet is required in addition to increased availability.
[src:profinet/profinet] Ethernet Advanced Physical Layer (Ethernet-APL) describes a physical layer for the Ethernet communication technology which is especially developed for the requirements of the process industries.
[src:profinet/profinet] The development of Ethernet-APL was determined by the need for communication at high speeds and over long distances, the supply of power and communications signals via common single, twisted-pair (2-wire) cable as well as protective measures for the safe use within explosion hazardous areas.
[src:profinet/profinet] Ethernet APL opens the possibility for Profinet to be incorporated into process instruments.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Profinet protocol can be recorded and displayed with any Ethernet analysis tool.
[src:profinet/profinet] Wireshark is capable of decoding Profinet telegrams.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Link Layer Discovery Protocol (LLDP) has been extended with additional parameters, so that in addition to the detection of neighbors, the propagation time of the signals on the connection lines can be communicated.
[src:profinet/profinet] The basic function of the Profinet is the cyclic data exchange between the IO-Controller as producer and several IO-Devices as consumers of the output data and the IO-Devices as producers and the IO-Controller as consumer of the input data.
[src:profinet/profinet] Each communication relationship **IO data CR** between the IO-Controller and an IO-Device defines the number of data and the cycle times.
[src:profinet/profinet] All Profinet IO-Devices must support device diagnostics and the safe transmission of alarms via the communication relation for alarms **Alarm CR**.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition, device parameters can be read and written with each Profinet device via the acyclic communication relation **Record Data CR**.
[src:profinet/profinet] The data set for the unique identification of an IO-Device, the *Identification and Maintenance Data Set 0* (I&M 0), must be installed by all Profinet IO-Devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] Optionally, further information can be stored in a standardized format as I&M 1–4.
[src:profinet/profinet] For real-time data (cyclic data and alarms), the Profinet *Real-Time* (RT) telegrams are transmitted directly via Ethernet.
[src:profinet/profinet] UDP/IP is used for the transmission of acyclic data.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Application Relation (AR) is established between an IO-Controller and every IO-Device to be controlled.
[src:profinet/profinet] Inside the ARs are defined the required CRs.
[src:profinet/profinet] The Profinet AR life-cycle consists of address resolution, connection establishment, parameterization, process IO data exchange / alarm handling, and termination.
[src:profinet/profinet] **Connection establishment:** Connection establishment starts with the IO-Controller sending a *connect request* to the IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] The connect request establishes an *Application Relationship* (AR) containing a number of *Communication Relationships* (CRs) between the IO-Controller and IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition to the AR and CRs, the connect request specifies the modular configuration of the IO-Device, the layout of the process IO data frames, the cyclic rate of IO data exchange and the watchdog.
[src:profinet/profinet] Acknowledgement of the connect request by the IO-Device allows parameterization to follow.
[src:profinet/profinet] From this point forward, both the IO-Device and IO-Controller start exchanging cyclic process I/O data frames.
[src:profinet/profinet] The process I/O data frames don't contain valid data at this point, but they start serving as keep-alive to keep the watchdog from expiring.
[src:profinet/profinet] **Parameterization:** The IO-Controller writes parameterization data to each IO-Device sub-module in accordance with the *General Station Description Mark-up Language* (GSDML) file.
[src:profinet/profinet] Once all sub-modules have been configured, the IO-Controller signals that parameterization has ended.
[src:profinet/profinet] The IO-Device responds by signaling application readiness, which allows process IO data exchange and alarm handling to ensue.
[src:profinet/profinet] **Process IO data exchange / alarm handling:** The IO-Device followed by the IO-Controller start to cyclically refresh valid process I/O data.
[src:profinet/profinet] The IO-Controller processes the inputs and controls the outputs of the IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] Alarm notifications are exchanged acyclically between the IO-Controller and IO-Device as events and faults occur.
[src:profinet/profinet] **Termination:** The connection between the IO-Device and IO-Controller terminates when the watchdog expires.
[src:profinet/profinet] Watchdog expiry is the result of a failure to refresh cyclic process I/O data by the IO-Controller or the IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] Unless the connection was intentionally terminated at the IO-Controller, the IO-Controller will try to restart the Profinet Application Relation.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition to the basic Class A functions, Class B devices must support additional functionalities.
[src:profinet/profinet] These functionalities primarily support the commissioning, operation and maintenance of a Profinet IO system and are intended to increase the availability of the Profinet IO system.
[src:profinet/profinet] Support of network diagnostics with the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is mandatory.
[src:profinet/profinet] Likewise, the Link Layer Discovery Protocol (LLDP) for neighborhood detection including the extensions for Profinet must be supported by all Class B devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] This also includes the collection and provision of Ethernet port-related statistics for network maintenance.
[src:profinet/profinet] With these mechanisms, the **topology** of a Profinet IO network can be read out at any time and the status of the individual connections can be monitored.
[src:profinet/profinet] If the network topology is known, **automatic addressing** of the nodes can be activated by their position in the topology.
[src:profinet/profinet] This considerably simplifies device replacement during maintenance, since no more settings need to be made.
[src:profinet/profinet] High availability of the IO system is particularly important for applications in process automation and process engineering.
[src:profinet/profinet] For this reason, special procedures have been defined for Class B devices with the existing relationships and protocols.
[src:profinet/profinet] This allows **system redundancy** with two IO-Controllers accessing the same IO-Devices simultaneously.
[src:profinet/profinet] In addition, there is a prescribed procedure *Dynamic Reconfiguration* (DR), how the configuration of an IO-Device can be changed with the help of these redundant relationships without losing control over the IO-Device.
[src:profinet/profinet] For the functionalities of Conformance Class C (CC-C) the *Isochronous Real-Time* (IRT) protocol is mainly used.
[src:profinet/profinet] With the **bandwidth reservation**, a part of the available transmission bandwidth of 100 Mbit/s is reserved exclusively for real-time tasks.
[src:profinet/profinet] A procedure similar to a time multiplexing method is used.
[src:profinet/profinet] The bandwidth is divided into fixed cycle times, which in turn are divided into phases.
[src:profinet/profinet] The red phase is reserved exclusively for class C real-time data, in the orange phase the time-critical messages are transmitted and in the green phase the other Ethernet messages are transparently passed through.
[src:profinet/profinet] To ensure that maximum Ethernet telegrams can still be passed through transparently, the green phase must be at least 125 μs long.
[src:profinet/profinet] Thus, cycle times under 250 μs are not possible in combination with unchanged Ethernet.
[src:profinet/profinet] In order to achieve shorter cycle times down to 31.25 μs, the Ethernet telegrams of the green phase are optionally broken down into fragments.
[src:profinet/profinet] These short fragments are now transmitted via the green phase.
[src:profinet/profinet] This **fragmentation mechanism** is transparent to the other participants on the Ethernet and therefore not recognizable.
[src:profinet/profinet] In order to implement these bus cycles for bandwidth reservation, precise clock synchronization of all participating devices including the switches is required with a maximum deviation of 1 μs.
[src:profinet/profinet] This clock synchronization is implemented with the Precision Time Protocol (PTP) according to the IEEE 1588-2008 (1588 V2) standard.
[src:profinet/profinet] All devices involved in the bandwidth reservation must therefore be in the same time domain.
[src:profinet/profinet] For position control applications for several axes or for positioning processes according to the PROFIdrive drive profile of application classes 4 - 6, not only must communication be timely, but the actions of the various drives on a Profinet must also be coordinated and synchronized.
[src:profinet/profinet] The clock **synchronization** of the application program to the bus cycle allows control functions to be implemented that are executed synchronously on distributed devices.
[src:profinet/profinet] If several Profinet devices are connected in a line (daisy chain), it is possible to further optimise the cyclic data exchange with ***Dynamic Frame Packing*** (DFP).
[src:profinet/profinet] For this purpose, the controller puts all output data for all devices into a single IRT frame.
[src:profinet/profinet] At the passing IRT frame, each Device takes out the data intended for the device, i.e. the IRT frame becomes shorter and shorter.
[src:profinet/profinet] For the data from the different devices to the controller, the IRT frame is dynamically assembled.
[src:profinet/profinet] The great efficiency of the DFP lies in the fact that the IRT frame is always only as extensive as necessary and that the data from the controller to the devices can be transmitted in full duplex simultaneously with the data from the devices to the controller.
[src:profinet/profinet] Class D offers the same services to the user as Class C, with the difference that these services are provided using the mechanisms of Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN) defined by IEEE.
[src:profinet/profinet] The *Remote Service Interface* (RSI) is used as a replacement for the Internet protocol suite.
[src:profinet/profinet] Thus, this application class D is implemented independently of IP addresses.
[src:profinet/profinet] The protocol stack will be smaller and independent of future Internet versions (IPv6).
[src:profinet/profinet] The TSN is not a consistent, self-contained protocol definition, but a collection of different protocols with different characteristics that can be combined almost arbitrarily for each application.
[src:profinet/profinet] For use in industrial automation, a subset is compiled in IEC/IEEE standard 60802 "Joint Profile TSN for Industrial Automation".
[src:profinet/profinet] A subset is used in the Profinet specification version 2.4 for implementing class D.
[src:profinet/profinet] For the isochronous data exchange the clocks of the participants must be synchronized.
[src:profinet/profinet] For this purpose, the specifications of the Precision Time Protocol according to IEC 61588 for time synchronization with TSN are adapted accordingly.
[src:profinet/profinet] The telegrams are arranged in queues according to the priorities provided in the VLAN tag.
[src:profinet/profinet] The *Time-Aware Shaper* (TAS) now specifies a clock pulse with which the individual queues are processed in a switch.
[src:profinet/profinet] This leads to a time-slot procedure where the isochronous, cyclical data is transmitted with the highest priority, the cyclical data with the second priority before all acyclic data.
[src:profinet/profinet] This reduces the latency time and also the jitter for the cyclic data.
[src:profinet/profinet] If a data telegram with low priority lasts too long, it can be interrupted by a cyclic data telegram with high priority and transmitted further afterwards.
[src:profinet/profinet] This procedure is called **Frame Preemption** and is mandatory for CC-D.
[src:profinet/profinet] For the realization of a Profinet interface as controller or device, no additional hardware requirements are required for Profinet (CC-A and CC-B) that cannot be met by a common Ethernet interface (100BASE-TX or 100BASE-FX).
[src:profinet/profinet] To enable a simpler line topology, the installation of a switch with 2 ports in a device is recommended.
[src:profinet/profinet] For the realization of class C (CC-C) devices, an extension of the hardware with time synchronization with the Precision Time Protocol (PTP) and the functionalities of bandwidth reservation is required.
[src:profinet/profinet] For class D (CC-D) devices, the hardware must support the required functionalities of Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN) according to IEEE standards.
[src:profinet/profinet] The method of implementation depends on the design and performance of the device and the expected quantities.
[src:profinet/profinet] At the general meeting of the Profibus user organisation in 2000, the first concrete discussions for a successor to Profibus based on Ethernet took place.
[src:profinet/profinet] Just one year later, the first specification of *Component Based Automation* (CBA) was published and presented at the Hanover Fair.
[src:profinet/profinet] In 2002, the Profinet CBA became part of the international standard IEC 61158 / IEC 61784-1.
[src:profinet/profinet] A Profinet CBA system consists of different automation components.
[src:profinet/profinet] One component comprises all mechanical, electrical and information technology variables.
[src:profinet/profinet] The component may have been created with the usual programming tools.
[src:profinet/profinet] To describe a component, a *Profinet Component Description* (PCD) file is created in XML.
[src:profinet/profinet] A planning tool loads these descriptions and allows the logical connections between the individual components to be created to implement a plant.
[src:profinet/profinet] The basic idea behind Profinet CBA was that in many cases it is possible to divide an entire automation system into autonomously operating - and thus manageable - subsystems.
[src:profinet/profinet] The structure and functionality may well be found in several plants in identical or slightly modified form.
[src:profinet/profinet] Such so-called *Profinet components* are normally controlled by a manageable number of input signals.
[src:profinet/profinet] Within the component, a control program written by the user executes the required functionality and sends the corresponding output signals to another controller.
[src:profinet/profinet] The communication of a component-based system is planned instead of programmed.
[src:profinet/profinet] Communication with Profinet CBA was suitable for bus cycle times of approx.
[src:profinet/profinet] Individual systems show how these concepts can be successfully implemented in the application.
[src:profinet/profinet] However, Profinet CBA does not find the expected acceptance in the market and will no longer be listed in the IEC 61784-1 standard from the 4th edition of 2014.
[src:profinet/profinet] In 2003 the first specification of Profinet IO (IO = Input Output) was published.
[src:profinet/profinet] The application interface of the Profibus DP (DP = Decentralized Periphery), which was successful on the market, was adopted and supplemented with current protocols from the Internet.
[src:profinet/profinet] In the following year, the extension with isochronous transmission follows, which makes Profinet IO suitable for motion control applications.
[src:profinet/profinet] Profisafe is adapted so that it can also be used via Profinet.
[src:profinet/profinet] With the clear commitment of AIDA to Profinet in 2004, acceptance in the market is given.
[src:profinet/profinet] In 2006 Profinet IO becomes part of the international standard IEC 61158 / IEC 61784-2.
[src:profinet/profinet] In 2007, according to the neutral count, 1 million Profinet devices have already been installed, in the following year this number doubles to 2 million.
[src:profinet/profinet] By 2019, a total of 26 million devices sold by the various manufacturers are reported.
[src:profinet/profinet] In 2019, the specification for Profinet was completed with Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN), thus introducing the CC-D conformance class.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O), in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] They can be designed for many arrangements of digital and analog I/O, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs were first developed in the automobile manufacturing industry to provide flexible, rugged and easily programmable controllers to replace hard-wired relay logic systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Dick Morley, who invented the first PLC, the Modicon 084, for General Motors in 1968, is considered the father of PLC.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an example of a hard real-time system since output results must be produced in response to input conditions within a limited time, otherwise unintended operation may result.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC originated in the late 1960s in the automotive industry in the US and was designed to replace relay logic systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Before, control logic for manufacturing was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The hard-wired nature of these components made it difficult for design engineers to alter the automation process.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Changes would require rewiring and careful updating of the documentation.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] When general-purpose computers became available, they were soon applied to control logic in industrial processes.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These early computers were unreliable and required specialist programmers and strict control of working conditions, such as temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC provided several advantages over earlier automation systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It was designed to tolerate the industrial environment better than systems intended for office use, and was more reliable, compact, and required less maintenance than relay systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It was easily expandable with additional I/O modules.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] While relay systems required tedious and sometimes complicated hardware changes in case of reconfiguration, a PLC can be reconfigured by loading new or modified code.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] This allowed for easier iteration over manufacturing process design.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] With a simple programming language focused on logic and switching operations, it was more user-friendly than computers using general-purpose programming languages.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Early PLCs were programmed in ladder logic, which strongly resembled a schematic diagram of relay logic.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It also permitted its operation to be monitored.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In recent years, the introduction of virtual PLCs has expanded the scope of programmable logic controllers.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Virtual PLCs are software-based controllers that simulate the functions of traditional PLCs but are executed on general-purpose hardware, offering a more cost-effective and flexible alternative.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These controllers enable automation systems to be managed without the need for dedicated hardware, making them ideal for applications requiring simulation, remote control, or cloud-based systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In 1968, GM Hydramatic, the automatic transmission division of General Motors, issued a request for proposals for an electronic replacement for hard-wired relay systems based on a white paper written by engineer Edward R.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The winning proposal came from Bedford Associates from Bedford, Massachusetts.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The result, built in 1969, was the first PLC and designated the *084*, because it was Bedford Associates' eighty-fourth project.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Bedford Associates started a company, **Modicon, Inc.**, dedicated to developing, manufacturing, selling, and servicing this new product, which they named **Modicon** (standing for "modular digital controller").
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] One of the people who worked on that project was Dick Morley, who is considered to be the father of the PLC.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The Modicon brand was sold in 1977 to Gould Electronics and later to Schneider Electric, its current owner.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] About this same time, Modicon created Modbus, a data communications protocol to be used with its PLCs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Modbus has since become a standard open protocol commonly used to connect many industrial electrical devices.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] One of the first Modicon 084 models built is now on display at Schneider Electric's facility in North Andover, Massachusetts.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It was presented to Modicon by GM, when the unit was retired after nearly twenty years of uninterrupted service.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Modicon used the 84 moniker at the end of its product range like Modicon Micro 84 and Modicon TSX CSY 84 until after the 984 made its appearance.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In a parallel development, Odo Josef Struger is sometimes known as the "father of the programmable logic controller" as well.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] He was involved in the invention of the Allen-Bradley programmable logic controller.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the release of the IBM "Personal Computer" in 1981, these devices were commonly known simply as "Programmable Controllers", or "PC's.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] But rapid expansion of the personal computer industry in the early 1980's, the abbreviation "PC" was rapidly and universally accepted as a reference to "Personal Computers".
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Odo was later credited with coining the "PLC" acronym to distinguish these two technologies, And the inclusion of the word "Logic" was an easy choice as "Ladder Logic" had already been accepted as the name of the programming language.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley (now a brand owned by Rockwell Automation) went on to become the dominant PLC manufacturer in the United States during his tenure.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Struger played a leadership role in developing IEC 61131-3 PLC programming language standards.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley's PLC-5 family, preceded by the 1774-PLC (released in the 1980's, was the first modular design found in modern-day systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] While Modicon was the most popular of the first full featured PLC's through the early 1980's, Allen Bradley overtook them in the mid-1980's and grew to own the largest market share of PLC hardware and software in North America.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Many early PLC programming applications were not capable of graphical representation of the logic, and so it was instead represented as a series of logic expressions in some kind of Boolean format, similar to Boolean algebra.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] As programming terminals evolved, because ladder logic was a familiar format used for electro-mechanical control panels, it became more commonly used.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Newer formats, such as state logic, function block diagrams, and structured text exist.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Ladder logic remains popular because PLCs solve the logic in a predictable and repeating sequence, and ladder logic allows the person writing the logic to see any issues with the timing of the logic sequence more easily than would be possible in other formats.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Up to the mid-1990s, PLCs were programmed using proprietary programming panels or special-purpose programming terminals, which often had dedicated function keys representing the various logical elements of PLC programs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Some proprietary programming terminals displayed the elements of PLC programs as graphic symbols, but plain ASCII character representations of contacts, coils, and wires were common.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Programs were stored on cassette tape cartridges.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Facilities for printing and documentation were minimal due to a lack of memory capacity.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The oldest PLCs used magnetic-core memory.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an industrial microprocessor-based controller with programmable memory used to store program instructions and various functions.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs require a programming device that is used to develop and later download the created program into the memory of the controller.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs generally contain a real-time operating system, such as OS-9 or VxWorks.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] There are two types of mechanical design for PLC systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A *single box* (also called a *brick*) is a small programmable controller that fits all units and interfaces into one compact casing, although, typically, additional expansion modules for inputs and outputs are available.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The second design type – a *modular* PLC – has a chassis (also called a *rack*) that provides space for modules with different functions, such as power supply, processor, selection of I/O modules and communication interfaces – which all can be customized for the particular application.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Several racks can be administered by a single processor and may have thousands of inputs and outputs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Either a special high-speed serial I/O link or comparable communication method is used so that racks can be distributed away from the processor, reducing the wiring costs for large plants.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Discrete (digital) signals can only take *on* or *off* value (1 or 0, *true* or *false*).
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Examples of devices providing a discrete signal include limit switches and photoelectric sensors.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Analog signals can use voltage or current that is analogous to the monitored variable and can take any value within their scale.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Pressure, temperature, flow, and weight are often represented by analog signals.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically interpreted as integer values with various ranges of accuracy depending on the device and the number of bits available to store the data.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] For example, an analog 0 to 10 V or 4-20 mA current loop input would be converted into an integer value of 0 to 32,767.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC will take this value and translate it into the desired units of the process so the operator or program can read it.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Some special processes need to work permanently with minimum unwanted downtime.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Therefore, it is necessary to design a system that is fault tolerant.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In such cases, to increase the system availability in the event of hardware component failure, redundant CPU or I/O modules with the same functionality can be added to a hardware configuration to prevent a total or partial process shutdown due to hardware failure.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Other redundancy scenarios could be related to safety-critical processes, for example, large hydraulic presses could require that two PLCs turn on an output before the press can come down in case one PLC does not behave properly.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Programmable logic controllers are intended to be used by engineers without a programming background.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] For this reason, a graphical programming language called ladder logic was first developed.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It resembles the schematic diagram of a system built with electromechanical relays and was adopted by many manufacturers and later standardized in the IEC 61131-3 control systems programming standard.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, it is still widely used, thanks to its simplicity.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, the majority of PLC systems adhere to the IEC 61131-3 standard that defines two textual programming languages: Structured Text (similar to Pascal) and Instruction List; as well as three graphical languages: ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Instruction List was deprecated in the third edition of the standard.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs can be programmed in a variety of ways, from the relay-derived ladder logic to programming languages such as specially adapted dialects of BASIC and C.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] While the fundamental concepts of PLC programming are common to all manufacturers, differences in I/O addressing, memory organization, and instruction sets mean that PLC programs are never perfectly interchangeable between different makers.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Even within the same product line of a single manufacturer, different models may not be directly compatible.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Manufacturers develop programming software for their PLCs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In addition to being able to program PLCs in multiple languages, they provide common features like hardware diagnostics and maintenance, software debugging, and offline simulation.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLC programs are typically written in a programming device, which can take the form of a desktop console, special software on a personal computer, or a handheld device.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The program is then downloaded to the PLC through a cable connection or over a network.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It is stored either in non-volatile flash memory or battery-backed-up RAM on the PLC.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In some PLCs, the program is transferred from the programming device using a programming board that writes the program into a removable chip, such as EPROM, that is then inserted into the PLC.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] An incorrectly programmed PLC can result in lost productivity and dangerous conditions for programmed equipment.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLC simulation is a feature often found in PLC programming software.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It allows for testing and debugging early in a project's development.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Testing the project in simulation improves its quality, increases the level of safety associated with equipment and can save time during the installation and commissioning of automated control applications since many scenarios can be tried and tested before the system is activated.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The main difference compared to most other computing devices is that PLCs are intended for and therefore tolerant of more severe environmental conditions (such as dust, moisture, heat, cold), while offering extensive input/output (I/O) to connect the PLC to sensors and actuators.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLC input can include simple digital elements such as limit switches, analog variables from process sensors (such as temperature and pressure), and more complex data such as that from positioning or machine vision systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLC output can include elements such as indicator lamps, sirens, electric motors, pneumatic or hydraulic cylinders, magnetic relays, solenoids, or analog outputs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The input/output arrangements may be built into a simple PLC, or the PLC may have external I/O modules attached to a fieldbus or computer network that plugs into the PLC.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The functionality of the PLC has evolved over the years to include sequential relay control, motion control, process control, distributed control systems, and networking.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The data handling, storage, processing power, and communication capabilities of some modern PLCs are approximately equivalent to desktop computers.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLC-like programming combined with remote I/O hardware allows a general-purpose desktop computer to serve as a PLC in certain applications.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The most basic function of a programmable logic controller is to emulate the functions of electromechanical relays.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Within the PLC programming environment, discrete inputs are given a unique address, and a PLC instruction can test if the input state is on or off.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Just as a series of relay contacts performs a logical AND function, not allowing current to pass unless all the contacts are closed, so a series of *examine if on* instructions will energize its output storage bit if all the input bits are on.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Similarly, a parallel set of instructions will perform a logical OR.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In an electromechanical relay wiring diagram, a group of contacts controlling one coil is called a *rung* of a *ladder diagram*, and this concept is also used to describe PLC logic.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The output of each rung sets or clears a storage bit, which may be associated with a discrete output or which may be an *internal coil* with no physical connection.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Such internal coils can be used, for example, as a common element in multiple separate rungs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] More advanced instructions of the PLC may be implemented as functional blocks, which carry out some operation, such as manipulating an internal variable, when enabled by a logical input and which produce outputs to signal, for example, completion or errors.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs use built-in ports, such as USB, Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485, or RS-422 to communicate with external devices (sensors, actuators) and systems (programming tools, SCADA and other user interfaces).
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Communication is carried over various industrial network protocols, like Modbus, or EtherNet/IP.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Many of these protocols are vendor specific.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Formerly, some manufacturers offered dedicated communication modules as an add-on function where the processor had no network connection built in.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs used in larger I/O systems may have peer-to-peer (P2P) communication between processors.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] This allows separate parts of a complex process to have individual control while allowing the subsystems to coordinate over the communication link.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs may need to interact with people for the purpose of configuration, alarm reporting, or everyday control.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A human-machine interface (HMI) is employed for this purpose.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] HMIs are also referred to as man-machine interfaces (MMIs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A simple system may use buttons and lights to interact with the user.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Text displays are available as well as graphical touch screens.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] More complex systems use programming and monitoring software installed on a computer, with the PLC connected via a communication interface.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC works in a program scan cycle, where it executes its program repeatedly.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The program follows the sequence of instructions.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] It typically takes a time span of tens of milliseconds for the processor to evaluate all the instructions and update the status of all outputs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] If the system contains remote I/O—for example, an external rack with I/O modules—then that introduces additional uncertainty in the response time of the PLC system.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Special-purpose I/O modules may be used where the scan time of the PLC is too long to allow predictable performance.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Precision timing modules, or counter modules for use with shaft encoders, are used where the scan time would be too long to reliably count pulses or detect the sense of rotation of an encoder.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] This allows even a relatively slow PLC to still interpret the counted values to control a machine, as the accumulation of pulses is done by a dedicated module that is unaffected by the speed of program execution.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] As PLCs became more advanced, methods were developed to change the sequence of ladder execution, and subroutines were implemented.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the discovery of the Stuxnet computer worm in June 2010, the security of PLCs received little attention.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Modern programmable controllers generally contain real-time operating systems, which can be vulnerable to exploits in a similar way as desktop operating systems.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can also be attacked by gaining control of a computer they communicate with.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Since 2011, these concerns have grown as networking is becoming more commonplace in the PLC environment, connecting the previously separated plant floor networks and office networks.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In February 2021, Rockwell Automation publicly disclosed a critical vulnerability affecting its Logix controller family.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The secret cryptographic key used to verify communication between the PLC and workstation could be extracted from the programming software (Studio 5000 Logix Designer) and used to remotely change program code and configuration of a connected controller.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The vulnerability was given a severity score of 10 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Safety PLCs can be either a standalone device or safety-rated hardware and functionality added to existing controller architectures (Allen-Bradley GuardLogix, Siemens F-series, etc.).
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These differ from conventional PLC types by being suitable for safety-critical applications for which PLCs have traditionally been supplemented with hard-wired safety relays and areas of the memory dedicated to the safety instructions.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The standard of safety level is the safety integrity level (SIL).
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A safety PLC might be used to control access to a robot cell with trapped-key access, or to manage the shutdown response to an emergency stop button on a conveyor production line.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Such PLCs typically have a restricted regular instruction set augmented with safety-specific instructions designed to interface with emergency stop buttons, light screens, and other safety-related devices.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs are well adapted to a range of automation tasks.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically industrial processes in manufacturing where the cost of developing and maintaining the automation system is high relative to the total cost of the automation system, and where changes to the system would be expected during its operational life.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs contain input and output devices compatible with industrial devices and controls; little electrical design is required, and the design problem centers on expressing the desired sequence of operations.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] PLC applications are typically highly customized systems, so the cost of a packaged PLC is low compared to the cost of a specific custom-built controller design.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] On the other hand, in the case of mass-produced goods, customized control systems are economical.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] This is due to the lower cost of the components, which can be optimally chosen instead of a *generic* solution, and where the non-recurring engineering charges are spread over thousands or millions of units.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These are for small machines and systems with low or medium volume.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] They can execute PLC languages such as ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] They are similar to traditional PLCs, but their small size allows developers to design them into custom printed circuit boards like a microcontroller, without computer programming knowledge, but with a language that is easy to use, modify and maintain.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Architecturally, they sit between the classic PLC or micro-PLC and microcontrollers.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Automotive applications are an example; millions of units are built each year, and very few end-users alter the programming of these controllers.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] However, some specialty vehicles, such as transit buses, economically use PLCs instead of custom-designed controllers, because the volumes are low and the development cost would be uneconomical.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Very complex process control, such as that used in the chemical industry, may require algorithms and performance beyond the capability of even high-performance PLCs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Very high-speed or precision controls may also require customized solutions; for example, aircraft flight controls.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Single-board computers using semi-customized or fully proprietary hardware may be chosen for very demanding control applications where the high development and maintenance cost can be supported.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] **Soft PLCs** running on desktop-type computers can interface with industrial I/O hardware while executing programs within a version of commercial operating systems adapted for process control needs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] The rising popularity of single-board computers has also had an influence on the development of PLCs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Traditional PLCs are generally closed platforms, but some newer PLCs (e.g., groov EPIC from Opto 22, ctrlX from Bosch Rexroth, PFC200 from Wago, PLCnext from Phoenix Contact, and Revolution Pi from Kunbus) provide the features of traditional PLCs on an open platform.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In more recent years, small products called programmable logic relays (PLRs) or smart relays have become more common and accepted.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These are similar to PLCs and are used in light industries where only a few points of I/O are needed, and low cost is desired.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] These small devices are typically made in a common physical size and shape by several manufacturers and branded by the makers of larger PLCs to fill their low-end product range.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Most of these have 8 to 12 discrete inputs, 4 to 8 discrete outputs, and up to 2 analog inputs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Most have an RS-232 or RS-485 port for connecting to a PC so that programmers can use user-friendly software for programming instead of the small LCD and push-button set for this purpose.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike regular PLCs that are usually modular and greatly expandable, the PLRs are usually not modular or expandable, but their cost can be significantly lower than that a PLC, and they still offer robust design and deterministic execution of the logic.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] A variant of PLCs, used in remote locations, is the remote terminal unit or RTU.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] An RTU is typically a low power, ruggedized PLC whose key function is to manage the communications links between the site and the central control system (typically SCADA) or in some modern systems, "The Cloud".
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike factory automation using wired communication protocols such as Ethernet, communications links to remote sites are often radio-based and are less reliable.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] To account for the reduced reliability, RTU will buffer messages or switch to alternate communications paths.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] When buffering messages, the RTU will timestamp each message so that a full history of site events can be reconstructed.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] RTUs, being PLCs, have a wide range of I/O and are fully programmable, typically with languages from the IEC 61131-3 standard that is common to many PLCs, RTUs and DCSs.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] In remote locations, it is common to use an RTU as a gateway for a PLC, where the PLC is performing all site control and the RTU is managing communications, time-stamping events and monitoring ancillary equipment.
[src:profinet/programmable-logic-controller] On sites with only a handful of I/O, the RTU may also be the site PLC and will perform both communications and control functions.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:profinet/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
